The HTML form doesn&#39;t accept `PUT` as method. It only works with `GET` and `POST`. Have a look [here](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/form#attr-method). So if you write

```html
&lt;form method=&quot;PUT&quot;&gt;&lt;/form&gt;
```

you&#39;re going to submit the form as a `GET` request. Laravel listens for a specific input that has to present after form submission in order to recognize the `PUT` method. Have a look at the [official documentation](https://laravel.com/docs/6.x/routing#form-method-spoofing)

&gt; HTML forms do not support PUT, PATCH or DELETE actions. So, when defining PUT, PATCH or DELETE routes that are called from an HTML form, you will need to add a hidden _method field to the form. The value sent with the _method field will be used as the HTTP request method:

```php
&lt;form action=&quot;/foo/bar&quot; method=&quot;POST&quot;&gt;
    &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;_method&quot; value=&quot;PUT&quot;&gt;
    &lt;input type=&quot;hidden&quot; name=&quot;_token&quot; value=&quot;{{ csrf_token() }}&quot;&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
```

You may use the @method Blade directive to generate the _method input:

```php
&lt;form action=&quot;/foo/bar&quot; method=&quot;POST&quot;&gt;
    @method(&#39;PUT&#39;)
    @csrf
&lt;/form&gt;
```

